.452933Z"}},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 1400x500 with 2 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}},{"name":"stdout","text":"Saved: gating_analysis.png\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":19},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## Findings\nThe gating weight analysis provides indirect empirical validation of the cross-modal attention architecture's design rationale. The learned router assigns dominant weight to the cross-modal attention model in grid cells with mean soil moisture of 0.054 m³/m³, where the dust event rate is 14.2%, and defers to the late-fusion model in cells with mean soil moisture of 0.113 m³/m³, where the dust event rate falls to 4.3%. This is consistent with the foundational physics of dust emission as parameterised by Fecan et al. (1999), which establishes soil moisture as the primary modulator of the threshold friction velocity below which no emission occurs. The mixture-of-experts framework did not receive soil moisture as a label or target. The routing behaviour emerged from training on prediction errors alone, suggesting that the cross-modal attention model learned a representation that is specifically useful in the physically critical low-moisture regime.","metadata":{}}]}